{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 21:58:14.334121", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — SDN spine–leaf lab\\nTimestamp: (based on collected state)\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- Control/management plane (20.0.0.0/24) is reachable: the controller 20.0.0.100 is reachable from leaf_1, leaf_2 and spine_1.\\n- Data plane (tenant/subnet 10.0.0.0/24) appears non-functional: hosts in 10.0.0.0/24 cannot reach other hosts (even same-leaf peers). Pings between hosts return \"Destination Host Unreachable.\"\\n- Root cause (high confidence): the Open vSwitch datapaths/bridges on the switches (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1) are not up/active (ovs-system / OVS bridges are down), so L2 forwarding for the 10.0.0.0/24 tenant network is broken even though management interfaces are up.\\n\\nEvidence and observations\\n1) Host addressing and link state (hosts)\\n- host_1_1: eth0 = 10.0.0.1/24, interface UP, TX packets shown but no RX bytes.\\n- host_1_2: eth0 = 10.0.0.2/24, interface UP.\\n- host_2_1: eth0 = 10.0.0.9/24, host_2_2: eth0 = 10.0.0.10/24.\\n(Hosts are correctly configured with 10.0.0.0/24 addresses.)\\n\\n2) Switch interfaces and management IPs\\n- leaf_1: eth12 = 20.0.0.5/24 configured (management IP present).\\n- leaf_2: eth12 = 20.0.0.6/24 configured.\\n- spine_1: eth8 = 20.0.0.1/24 configured.\\n(Management interfaces and addresses are present and reachable.)\\n\\n3) OVS / bridge state (critical)\\n- leaf_1: the ip output shows \"ovs-system: state DOWN\" and \"leaf_1: … state DOWN\" (bridge(s) are present but down).\\n- leaf_2: same: \"ovs-system: state DOWN\" and \"leaf_2: … state DOWN\".\\n- spine_1: \"ovs-system: state DOWN\" and \"spine_1: … state DOWN\".\\n(ovs-system interfaces and the OVS bridge device names are in DOWN state — datapath/bridging not active.)\\n\\n4) Ping tests — data plane\\n- host_1_1 -> 10.0.0.2 (host_1_2): result = \"From 10.0.0.1 icmp_seq=N Destination Host Unreachable\" (100% loss).\\n- host_2_1 -> 10.0.0.10 (host_2_2): same \"Destination Host Unreachable\".\\n- host_1_1 -> 10.0.0.9 (host_2_1): same \"Destination Host Unreachable\".\\n(Hosts cannot reach other hosts on 10.0.0.0/24, including same-leaf peers.)\\n\\n5) Ping tests — management plane / controller\\n- leaf_1 -> 20.0.0.100: 3/3 replies, reasonable RTTs (avg ~21 ms with one high sample).\\n- leaf_2 -> 20.0.0.100: 3/3 replies, low RTT.\\n- spine_1 -> 20.0.0.100: 3/3 replies, low RTT.\\n(Management network connectivity and controller reachability are intact.)\\n\\nImpact / scope\\n- Affects all tenant hosts in 10.0.0.0/24 for inter-host connectivity — hosts cannot reach each other.\\n- Both leaves (leaf_1 and leaf_2) and spine (spine_1) show OVS bridges down; therefore the entire L2 fabric for the tenant network is impacted.\\n- Control-plane functions remain reachable (controller & management), so controller-to-switch connectivity over management network is working. The issue is localized to the data-plane switching layer on the switches.\\n\\nProbable root cause (diagnostic hypothesis)\\n- The Open vSwitch datapath(s)/bridges on the OVS switch nodes are not active (ovs-system and the named bridge devices show state DOWN). This prevents normal L2 switching/forwarding between host ports.\\n- Most likely causes that match the observed state:\\n  - The OVS user-space/datapath services (ovs-vswitchd/ovsdb-server) are not running or the OVS kernel datapath is not present, causing ovs-system and the per-switch bridge interfaces to be DOWN.\\n  - Alternatively, the OVS bridges exist but are administratively down or the bridge interfaces were not created/initialized (but interfaces for management are still configured).\\n- Evidence supporting this:\\n  - \"ovs-system: state DOWN\" and bridge devices (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1) reported as DOWN in the switch ip output.\\n  - Hosts show local \"Destination Host Unreachable\" when trying to reach same-subnet peers — consistent with lack of L2 connectivity/switching.\\n  - Management IPs and controller ping succeed, showing that only the data-plane (OVS) datapaths are affected.\\n\\nConfidence\\n- High confidence that OVS datapaths/bridges are the immediate cause of data-plane failure (direct evidence from ip/link state and host ping failures).\\n- Lower confidence on the underlying reason why OVS is down (service stopped, crash, kernel datapath missing, misconfiguration) — additional logs/commands required to determine exact root reason.\\n\\nRecommended next diagnostic data to collect (for root-cause confirmation)\\n- ovs-vsctl show (on leaf_1/leaf_2/spine_1) — to inspect bridge and port state.\\n- systemctl status/openvswitch status and journalctl logs for ovs-vswitchd and ovsdb-server on each switch host.\\n- dmesg / kernel logs for any datapath/kernel module errors (e.g., openvswitch module).\\n- ovs-ofctl show <bridge> to see whether flow tables exist and port states.\\n- Verify running processes: ps aux | grep ovs*\\n(These are diagnostic commands to collect more evidence; no remediation steps are included here.)\\n\\nSummary conclusion\\n- The network control plane (management) is up and the controller is reachable, but the data-plane L2 switching is not working because the OVS bridges/datapaths on the switches are down. This is isolating all hosts on the 10.0.0.0/24 tenant network from each other. The issue is confined to OVS/datapath functionality on the switch nodes (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1)., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='0b4290ce-85b6-4c5f-a564-c8638cb1669e'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
